{
 "cells": [
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "9de5361b",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Imports"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 83,
   "id": "39c35d86",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "from qiskit import *\n",
    "from qiskit.quantum_info import hellinger_fidelity\n",
    "\n",
    "from qiskit_aer import AerSimulator\n",
    "from qiskit_ibm_provider import IBMProvider\n",
    "\n",
    "# Plotting tools\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "import matplotlib_inline\n",
    "matplotlib_inline.backend_inline.set_matplotlib_formats('retina')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "ac9f5cac",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Setup"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "id": "ccb8f74a",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "provider = IBMProvider()\n",
    "backend = provider.get_backend(\"ibm_peekskill\")\n",
    "ideal_simulator = AerSimulator()\n",
    "noisy_simulator = AerSimulator.from_backend(backend)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "id": "43f56fa8",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1123.61x535.111 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 3,
     "metadata": {
      "image/png": {
       "height": 432,
       "width": 885
      }
     },
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "def bv_ones_circs(N):\n",
    "    \"\"\"Create a Bernstein-Vazirani circuit with all-ones oracle of width N\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    qc = QuantumCircuit(N, N-1)\n",
    "    qc.x(N-1)\n",
    "    qc.h(range(N))\n",
    "    qc.cx(range(N-1), N-1)\n",
    "    qc.h(range(N-1))\n",
    "    qc.barrier()\n",
    "    qc.measure(range(N-1), range(N-1))\n",
    "    return qc\n",
    "\n",
    "N = 5\n",
    "qc = bv_ones_circs(N)\n",
    "qc.draw('mpl')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "a28a97a4",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Now, obviously we can run this circuit (after transpiling) on IBM Quantum hardware. However, this circuit has a couple of issues that limit the output fidelity. (1) The circuits requires $N+1$\n",
    " qubits to encode a length $N$ bit-string. (2) On the current fleet of IBM Quantum systems based on the heavy-hex architecture, any algorithm requiring more than 3 CNOT gates per qubit needs to be re-routed to match the constraints of the device, adding additional swap gates.\n",
    "\n",
    "Obviously, if we wanted to extend our BV circuits to larger numbers of qubits, then the additional swaps would greatly limit the resulting fidelity. We can see this easily with a noisy simulator and/or execution on hardware."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "1e080c91",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Typical Execution"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "88ec7029",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Now we will generate BV circuits for all-ones bit-string (worst case scenario) of length from $2$ to $12$"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "id": "63f512f9",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "MAX_BITS = 10\n",
    "bv_circs = [bv_ones_circs(N) for N in range(2, MAX_BITS+1)]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 5,
   "id": "98a95ad5",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "trans_bv_circs = transpile(bv_circs, backend=backend, optimization_level=3)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 6,
   "id": "bb4ca216",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "ideal_counts = ideal_simulator.run(trans_bv_circs, shots=10000).result().get_counts()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 7,
   "id": "566e2b5d",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "noisy_sim_counts = noisy_simulator.run(trans_bv_circs, shots=10000).result().get_counts()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 8,
   "id": "365ebc6b",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "noisy_sim_fidelities = [hellinger_fidelity(noisy, ideal) for noisy, ideal in zip(noisy_sim_counts, ideal_counts)]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 9,
   "id": "a4c9cfd8",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "real_counts = backend.run(trans_bv_circs, shots=10000).result().get_counts()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 11,
   "id": "049555f0",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "real_fidelities = [hellinger_fidelity(real, ideal) for real, ideal in zip(real_counts, ideal_counts)]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 84,
   "id": "2a19f483",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 640x480 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "image/png": {
       "height": 432,
       "width": 567
      }
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "fig, ax = plt.subplots()\n",
    "ax.plot(range(2, MAX_BITS+1), noisy_sim_fidelities, \"o--\", ms=10, label='Simulation')\n",
    "ax.plot(range(2, MAX_BITS+1), real_fidelities, \"o--\", ms=10, label='Hardware')\n",
    "ax.set_xlabel('Bits')\n",
    "ax.set_ylabel('Fidelity')\n",
    "ax.legend();"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "7dace70f",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Dynamic Circuits"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "110a9561",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Up until now we have focused on circuits with a set pattern of instructions: gates, measurements, etc. It is a deterministic execution model."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "2a4fade7",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "As in classical computation, the richness of expression that is offered by flow-control in quantum circuits allows us to perform computations that are more efficient, or would otherwise be impossible.\n",
    "\n",
    "Our first dynamic operation is the `reset` operation, that returns the qubit to the $|0\\rangle$ state:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 13,
   "id": "90eb0a6d",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 185.453x117.056 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 13,
     "metadata": {
      "image/png": {
       "height": 110,
       "width": 162
      }
     },
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "qc_reset = QuantumCircuit(1)\n",
    "qc_reset.reset(0)\n",
    "qc_reset.draw('mpl')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "dbbe2e73",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Although it looks like any other operation, on IBM Quantum systems the reset operation is actually dynamic, consisting of a measurement operation followed by an x-gate conditioned on the (classical) value of the measurement.\n",
    "\n",
    "This can be written in Qiskit in the following way:\n",
    "\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 14,
   "id": "a4739333",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 352.675x200.667 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 14,
     "metadata": {
      "image/png": {
       "height": 174,
       "width": 291
      }
     },
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "qc = QuantumCircuit(1, 1)\n",
    "qc.measure(0, 0)\n",
    "\n",
    "# If bit 0 is 1, perform an x-gate, else do nothing\n",
    "with qc.if_test((0, True)):\n",
    "    qc.x(0)\n",
    "\n",
    "qc.draw('mpl')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "c7230882",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "This can also be written in the older `c_if` (classical-if) way by doing:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 15,
   "id": "bc985cc7",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 269.064x200.667 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 15,
     "metadata": {
      "image/png": {
       "height": 174,
       "width": 227
      }
     },
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "qc = QuantumCircuit(1, 1)\n",
    "qc.measure(0, 0)\n",
    "qc.x(0).c_if(0, True) #If bit 0 is True (1) do x-gate on Q0\n",
    "qc.draw('mpl')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "23939142",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "So we see that `reset` is nothing more than fixing the state of the qubit via measurement, and then flipping the bit if it is found to be in the $|1\\rangle$ state. Reset by itself has limited use outside of qubit initialization at the beginning of a circuit. However, the combination of `measurement`+`reset` is a critical component of many dynamic circuits as it allows for qubit measurement and recycling."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "5301ef99",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# BV as a dynamic circuit"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "f04d8839",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The BV circuit is an example of a circuit that benefits from qubit recycling. To see how this works, let us look at the basic building block of the BV circuit"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 16,
   "id": "c2149606",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 2043.33x535.111 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 16,
     "metadata": {
      "image/png": {
       "height": 432,
       "width": 1593
      }
     },
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "qc = QuantumCircuit(5, 4)\n",
    "qc.x(4)\n",
    "qc.h(4)\n",
    "qc.barrier()\n",
    "\n",
    "for i in range(4):\n",
    "    qc.h(i)\n",
    "    qc.cx(i, 4)\n",
    "    qc.h(i)\n",
    "    qc.measure(i, i)\n",
    "    qc.barrier()\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "qc.draw(\"mpl\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "5db34cb5",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "If we could reuse qubits, then the computation of any number of bits would require at most two-qubits. With `measure`+`reset` pairs (dynamic circuits) at our disposal, we can thus greatly improve the output fidelity of our BV circuits on hardware."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 17,
   "id": "20f5cd57",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def dynamic_bv(bitstring):\n",
    "    \"\"\"Create a Bernstein-Vazirani circuit from a given bitstring.\n",
    "    \n",
    "    Parameters:\n",
    "        bitstring (str): A bitstring.\n",
    "        \n",
    "    Returns:\n",
    "        QuantumCircuit: Output circuit.\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    qc = QuantumCircuit(2, len(bitstring))\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Prepare the |-x> state on target qubit\n",
    "    qc.x(1)\n",
    "    qc.h(1)\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # For each bit (0 or 1) build a simple circuit block\n",
    "    for idx, bit in enumerate(bitstring[::-1]):\n",
    "        \n",
    "        # Initial H gate on control\n",
    "        qc.h(0)\n",
    "        # If bit=1, do a CNOT gate\n",
    "        if int(bit):\n",
    "            qc.cx(0, 1)\n",
    "        # Final H gate to convert phase to computational-basis\n",
    "        qc.h(0)\n",
    "        # Measure\n",
    "        qc.measure(0,idx)\n",
    "        \n",
    "        # If not at the final bit, recycle and reset qubits\n",
    "        if idx != (len(bitstring)-1):\n",
    "            qc.barrier([0,1])\n",
    "            # Reset control qubit for reuse\n",
    "            qc.reset(0)\n",
    "            # reset target qubit to minimize dephasing\n",
    "            qc.reset(1)\n",
    "            # Prepare the |-x> state on target qubit again\n",
    "            qc.x(1)\n",
    "            qc.h(1)\n",
    "\n",
    "    return qc"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 18,
   "id": "056d651c",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 2210.35x618.722 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 18,
     "metadata": {
      "image/png": {
       "height": 496,
       "width": 1721
      }
     },
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "dyn_qc = dynamic_bv('1'*5)\n",
    "dyn_qc.draw('mpl')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 19,
   "id": "1b70cee8",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "dyn_ideal_counts = ideal_simulator.run(dyn_qc, shots=10000).result().get_counts()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 20,
   "id": "46c43e8d",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "{'11111': 10000}"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 20,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "dyn_ideal_counts"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "690d16d3",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Now, let us see how our dynamic BV circuits work on hardware:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 21,
   "id": "c61ac255",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "dyn_bv_circs = [dynamic_bv('1'*N) for N in range(2, MAX_BITS+1)]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 22,
   "id": "26528a10",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "dyn_trans_qc = transpile(dyn_bv_circs, backend, optimization_level=3)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 23,
   "id": "3fc58cb1",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "dyn_real_counts = backend.run(dyn_trans_qc, shots=10000).result().get_counts()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 25,
   "id": "d4209ad8",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "dyn_fidelities = [hellinger_fidelity(cnts, {'1'*(idx+2): 1}) for idx, cnts in enumerate(dyn_real_counts)]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 30,
   "id": "c77fcb07",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 640x480 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "image/png": {
       "height": 432,
       "width": 567
      }
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "fig, ax = plt.subplots()\n",
    "ax.plot(range(2, MAX_BITS+1), noisy_sim_fidelities, 'o--', ms=10, label='Simulation')\n",
    "ax.plot(range(2, MAX_BITS+1), real_fidelities, 'o--', ms=10, label='Hardware')\n",
    "ax.plot(range(2, MAX_BITS+1), dyn_fidelities, 'o--', ms=10, label='Dynamic-Hardware')\n",
    "ax.set_xlabel('Bits')\n",
    "ax.set_ylabel('Fidelity')\n",
    "ax.legend(); "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "d803c3d7",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Dynamic BV: further optimization"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "1e08acfb",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "In the dynamic version of BV circuits, there are `measure` operations followed by a `reset` operation. As mentioned, earlier, the `reset` operation in IBM systems is a `measure` followed by a conditional `X` gate. The full circuit looks like something like this"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 43,
   "id": "c9421a22",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 269.064x200.667 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 43,
     "metadata": {
      "image/png": {
       "height": 174,
       "width": 227
      }
     },
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "qc = QuantumCircuit(1, 1)\n",
    "qc.measure(0, 0)\n",
    "qc.reset(0)\n",
    "qc.draw('mpl')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 31,
   "id": "7fabd5b9",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 352.675x200.667 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 31,
     "metadata": {
      "image/png": {
       "height": 174,
       "width": 291
      }
     },
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "qc2 = QuantumCircuit(1, 2)\n",
    "qc2.measure(0, 0)\n",
    "qc2.measure(0, 1)\n",
    "qc2.x(0).c_if(1, True)\n",
    "qc2.draw('mpl')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "5c06c325",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Now, we have already seen that measurements are the most error prone operations on IBM Quantum systems, and take quite a bit of time (~2 CX gates worth of time). On this device, the average measurement error rate is"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 85,
   "id": "e4dd0c9c",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "0.015459259259259254"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 85,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "np.mean([backend.properties().readout_error(i) for i in range(backend.num_qubits)])"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "f6b3a5e0",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "So every `measure`+`reset` pair is quite costly in terms of both error and duration. If we could reduce the number of measurements, then the performance would greatly improve. It turns out that we can. The back-to-back measurments in the above case are done immediately, and therefore, a qubit state does not have the scope to evolve between the measurements. In other words, qubit state remains same between those immediate back-to-back measurements.\n",
    "\n",
    "Thus, instead of back-to-back measurements, we can do only the first measurement and apply the conditional `X` gate based on that measurement outcome, and in the process, can omit one costly `measure` operation. (This is an example of the Zeno effect; the state of a system is frozen upon fast repeated measurements.)\n",
    "\n",
    "Because `measure`+`reset` are so ubiquitous in dynamic circuits, Qiskit can auto-simplify combinations of operations. This is done via the `ResetAfterMeasureSimplification` transpiler pass:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 39,
   "id": "96b01dd3",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from qiskit.transpiler import PassManager\n",
    "from qiskit.transpiler.passes.optimization import ResetAfterMeasureSimplification"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 40,
   "id": "9c066012",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "pm = PassManager(ResetAfterMeasureSimplification())"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 44,
   "id": "27c97ec2",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 269.064x200.667 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 44,
     "metadata": {
      "image/png": {
       "height": 174,
       "width": 227
      }
     },
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "collapsed_qc = pm.run(qc)\n",
    "collapsed_qc.draw('mpl')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "b950a569",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We are now in a position to further optimize our dynamic BV circuits by collapsing `measure`+`reset` pairs down to just a single measurement and conditional `X`-gate. However, our barrier placement up until now prevents us from optimizing this via Qiskit. As such, we need to define a new set of circuits (instead of having the `measure` and `reset` operations on the opposite side of a barrier, the new circuits will have them after the barrier):"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",

   "source": [
    "def dynamic_bv2(bitstring):\n",
    "    \"\"\"Create a Bernstein-Vazirani circuit from a given bitstring.\n",
    "    \n",
    "    Parameters:\n",
    "        bitstring (str): A bitstring.\n",
    "        \n",
    "    Returns:\n",
    "        QuantumCircuit: Output circuit.\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    qc = QuantumCircuit(2, len(bitstring))\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Prepare the |-x> state on target qubit\n",
    "    qc.x(1)\n",
    "    qc.h(1)\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # For each bit (0 or 1) build a simple circuit block\n",
    "    for idx, bit in enumerate(bitstring[::-1]):\n",
    "        \n",
    "        # Initial H gate on control\n",
    "        qc.h(0)\n",
    "        # If bit=1, do a CNOT gate\n",
    "        if int(bit):\n",
    "            qc.cx(0, 1)\n",
    "        # Final H gate to convert phase to computational-basis\n",
    "        qc.h(0)\n",
    "        # Measure\n",
    "        qc.barrier([0,1])\n",
    "        qc.measure(0,idx)\n",
    "        # If not at the final bit, recycle and reset qubits\n",
    "        if idx != (len(bitstring)-1):\n",
    "            # Reset control qubit for reuse\n",
    "            qc.reset(0)\n",
    "            # reset target qubit to minimize dephasing\n",
    "            qc.reset(1)\n",
    "            #qc.barrier([0,1])\n",
    "            # Prepare the |-x> state on target qubit again\n",
    "            qc.x(1)\n",
    "            qc.h(1)\n",
    "\n",
    "    return qc"
   ]
  },

   "source": [
    "dyn_bv_circs2 = [dynamic_bv2('1'*N) for N in range(2,MAX_BITS+1)]"
   ]
